	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_65285915"><p><div class="quote"><p>A common theme I'll see in mentions of planned missions to Mars is that it would last about 2 years due to how the orbits of Mars and Earth align, this often coincides with the idea of a Mars Cycler: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mars_cycler" title="wikipedia.org">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/...</a> [wikipedia.org] </p></div><p>
The cycler just seems to make lots of sense.  I'm surprised it hasn't been attempted as a method to move probes and other unmanned craft to Mars and back. Or on a smaller scale, a lunar cycler.  The propulsion needs for interplanetary travel are different than the needs for takeoff and landing.  Separating them into two different craft just seems like a good idea to try.</p></div>
	</div>

